If you create a rect plane and apply a texture on it, you'll get a vertically flipped image.

``` java
private ModelInstance createPlane(float z, Texture texture) {

        int width = texture.getWidth();
        int height = texture.getHeight();

        Vector3 _00, _01, _10, _11, norm;

        _00 = new Vector3();
        _01 = new Vector3();
        _10 = new Vector3();
        _11 = new Vector3();
        norm = new Vector3();


        Material material = new Material();
        TextureAttribute textureAttribute = new TextureAttribute(TextureAttribute.Diffuse, texture);

        material.set(textureAttribute);
        material.set(new BlendingAttribute(GL20.GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL20.GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA));

        Model model = null;
        ModelBuilder mb = new ModelBuilder();
        mb.begin();

        MeshPartBuilder part = mb.part("rect", GL20.GL_TRIANGLES,  VertexAttributes.Usage.Position | VertexAttributes.Usage.Normal | VertexAttributes.Usage.TextureCoordinates, material);

        _11.set( width / 2,   height / 2, z);         // right up
        _01.set(-width / 2,   height / 2, z);         // left up

        _00.set(-width / 2,  -height / 2, z);         // left bottom
        _10.set( width / 2,  -height / 2, z);         // right bottom

        norm = new Vector3(0, 0, -1);

        // part.setUVRange(0, 1, 1, 0); // this line fixes the problem!!!!

        part.rect(_00, _10, _11, _01, norm);
        model = mb.end();

        model.manageDisposable(texture);
        ModelInstance modelInstance = new ModelInstance(model);

        modelInstance.transform.setToTranslation(0, 0, 0);

        return modelInstance;
    }
```

If you create a plane passing a texture created with 

``` java
new Texture(Gdx.files.internal("data/someimage.jpg")
```

The resulting image is vertically flipped.

If you uncomment the "part.setUVRange" line everything works as expected.
